<doc id="86082" wikidata="Q596647" url="?curid=86082" title="Fiacha mac Delbaíth">
<text>In Irish mythology, Fiacha (, sometimes Fiachu, Fiachra or Fiachna), son of Delbáeth, of the Tuatha Dé Danann, was a legendary High King of Ireland. According to the &quot;Lebor Gabála Érenn&quot;, he took the throne after his father was overthrown by Caicher son of Nama, brother of Nechtan. The &quot;Annals of the Four Masters&quot; and Geoffrey Keating say he overthrew his father himself. His mother was Ernmas. He had three daughters, Banba, Fódla, and Ériu, by his own mother. He reigned for ten years, before he and his nephew Aoi Mac Ollamain were killed in battle against Éogan of Imber.

