<doc id="86084" wikidata="Q4876081" url="?curid=86084" title="Beag">
<text>In Irish mythology, Bec (modern Irish &quot;Beag&quot;, meaning &quot;small&quot;) was one of the Tuatha Dé Danann. She was known for having a magic well, that would grant wisdom with one drink and foretelling for a second. The well was guarded by her three daughters. When Fionn mac Cumhaill approached the well to ask for a drink, her daughters tried to prevent him from getting the water; &quot;one of them threw water over him to scare him away and some of it went into his mouth. From the water he gained wisdom.&quot;

