<doc id="86116" wikidata="Q2297836" url="?curid=86116" title="Tuireann">
<text>In Irish mythology, Tuireann (Old Irish: Tuirenn or Tuirill Biccreo) was the father by Danu (or Brigid) of Creidhne, Luchtaine, and Goibniu.

His other sons included Brian, Iuchar, and Iucharba, who killed Lugh&#x27;s father Cian. As an &quot;erec&quot; (a recompense fine), they were sent on a quest recounted as&quot; Oidheadh Chlainne Tuireann&quot; (&quot;The Tragedy of the Sons of Tuireann&quot;), one of the &quot;Three sorrowful tales of Erin&quot;. After Lugh had taken his elaborate revenge, Tuireann died of grief over their graves.

He is stated in various portions of &quot;Lebor Gabála Érenn&quot; to be the same person as Delbáeth mac Ogma, who is also credited as the father of Brian, Iuchar, and Iucharba.

